Forest Cover Type Dataset

Stefano Merlo

1 Introduction

Scope of this analysis is to develop a model to predict the most present variety of tree for a given area, provided some geographical and terrain characteristics, learning from a 500k observation dataset, using k-nearest neighboor and random forest algorithms.

2 Get data and info

2.1 Load libraries and data

URL: https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/forest-cover-type-dataset

library(tidyverse)
# raw data
raw_data <- readr::read_csv("~/Downloads/forest-trees/covtype.csv", progress = FALSE)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_integer()
## )
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.
# maintain original raw data and create working dataset
dd <- raw_data %>% tbl_df()

2.2 Dataset metadata

This dataset is part of the UCI Machine Learning Repository. The original database owners are Jock A. Blackard, Dr. Denis J. Dean, and Dr. Charles W. Anderson of the Remote Sensing and GIS Program at Colorado State University.

It contains tree observations from four areas of the Roosevelt National Forest in Colorado. All observations are cartographic variables (no remote sensing) from 30 meter x 30 meter sections.

Variables:

  • Elevation: Elevation in meters
  • Aspect: Aspect in degrees azimuth. Aspect is the compass direction that a slope faces.
  • Slope: Slope in degrees
  • Horizontal Distance To Hydrology: Horz Dist to nearest surface water features
  • Vertical Distance To Hydrology: Vert Dist to nearest surface water features
  • Horizontal Distance To Roadways: Horz Dist to nearest roadway
  • Hillshade 9am (0 to 255 index): Hillshade index at 9am, summer solstice
  • Hillshade Noon (0 to 255 index): Hillshade index at noon, summer solstice
  • Hillshade 3pm (0 to 255 index): Hillshade index at 3pm, summer solstice
  • Horizontal Distance To Fire Points: Horz Dist to nearest wildfire ignition points
  • Wilderness Area (4 binary columns, 0 = absence or 1 = presence): Wilderness area designation
  • Soil Type (40 binary columns, 0 = absence or 1 = presence): Soil Type designation
  • Cover Type (7 types, integers 1 to 7): Forest Cover Type designation

3 Exploratory data analysis and metadata reshaping

3.1 Explore and uniform variables names and factor levels

names(dd) %>% tbl_df()
# remove capitalization and uniform names
names(dd) <- rattle::normVarNames(names(dd))
names(dd) %>% tbl_df()

3.2 Convert cover type to factor

cover_types <- tbl_df(data.frame(
    ct = 1:7,
    cover_type = c("Spruce/Fir",
          "Lodgepole Pine",
          "Ponderosa Pine",
          "Cottonwood/Willow",
          "Aspen",
          "Douglas-fir",
          "Krummholz"),
    stringsAsFactors = FALSE
))

# join cover types
dd <- dd %>%
  rename(ct = cover_type) %>%
  left_join(cover_types, by = "ct") %>%
  select(-ct) %>%
  mutate(cover_type = as.factor(cover_type))
  
# normalize factor levels
levels(dd$cover_type) <- rattle::normVarNames(levels(dd$cover_type))

dd <- dd %>%
  tidyr::gather(st, st_flag, soil_type_1:soil_type_40) %>%
  filter(st_flag != 0) %>%
  left_join(soil_types, by = "st") %>%
  select(-st, -st_flag) %>%
  mutate(soil_type = as.factor(soil_type))
  
# reshape wilderness area and convert to labels
dd <- dd %>%
  tidyr::gather(wa, wa_flag, wilderness_area_1:wilderness_area_4) %>%
  filter(wa_flag != 0) %>%
  left_join(wilderness_areas, by = "wa") %>%
  select(-wa, -wa_flag) %>%
  mutate(wilderness_area = as.factor(wilderness_area))

Save indexes of numerical variables is helpful for models that require specific classes as input.

vars <- names(dd)

# indexes of vars candidate inputs for modeling
not_target <- vars[vars != target]
not_target_indexes <- sapply(not_target, function(x) which(x == names(dd)),
                 USE.NAMES = FALSE)

# numerical variables
numeric_vars <- intersect(not_target_indexes,
                          which(sapply(dd, is.numeric)))

# categorical variables
categorical_vars <- intersect(not_target_indexes,
                              which(sapply(dd, is.factor)))

3.9 Check for highly correlated variables

mc <- cor(dd[which(sapply(dd, is.numeric))], use = "complete.obs")
mc[upper.tri(mc, diag = TRUE)] <- NA
mc %>%
  abs() %>%
  data.frame %>%
  tbl_df() %>%
  mutate(var1 = row.names(mc)) %>%
  gather(var2, cor, -var1) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  arrange(desc(cor)) %>%
  filter(cor > 0.5) %>%
  knitr::kable(digits = 3)
var1 var2 cor
hillshade_3pm hillshade_9am 0.780
hillshade_3pm aspect 0.647
vertical_distance_to_hydrology horizontal_distance_to_hydrology 0.606
hillshade_3pm hillshade_noon 0.594
hillshade_9am aspect 0.579
hillshade_noon slope 0.527

Highest correlation is between hillshade in the morning and in the afternoon, likely in areas where the sun is blocked by natural barriers only in certain periods of the day.

Same for hillshade and aspect: this is also expected by the definition of the variables: * aspect is the compass direction that a slope faces; * hillshade is an index for the illumination on summer solstice

dd %>%
  sample_n(500) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = aspect, y = hillshade_noon)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Aspect", y = "Hillshade at noon", title = "Hillshade by aspect")

When the aspect is around 180, so south-facing, the hillshade is maximun: this is correct since these wilderness areas are in the northern emisphere.

4.4 Hillshades

There are three different hillshade values, taken at three times of day.

# list of plots at all times of the day
plot_list <- list()
plot_list[[1]] <- dd %>%
  ggplot(aes_string(x = target, y = "hillshade_9am")) +
  geom_boxplot() + coord_flip()
plot_list[[2]] <- dd %>%
  ggplot(aes_string(x = target, y = "hillshade_noon")) +
  geom_boxplot() + coord_flip()
plot_list[[3]] <- dd %>%
  ggplot(aes_string(x = target, y = "hillshade_3pm")) +
  geom_boxplot() + coord_flip()

# plot all plots in a grid
GGally::ggmatrix(plot_list,
                 nrow = 1,
                 ncol = 3,
                 xAxisLabels = c("9am", "Noon", "3pm"),
                 yAxisLabels = "Cover Type",
                 title = "Cover type by hillshade")

Taken separately don’t seem a strong features, but I will try to create a new one by multiplying.

dd <- dd %>%
    mutate(hillshade_tot = hillshade_9am * hillshade_noon * hillshade_3pm)
dd %>%
  ggplot(aes_string(x = target, y = "hillshade_tot")) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "Cover Type",
       y = "Hillshade product of 9am, noon, 3pm",
       title = "Cover Type by engineered hillshade")

Slightly better but still a weak predictor.

5 Data Modeling

I will use the following models:

  • random forest
  • k-nearest neighboors

I will first run algorithms on a small subset, to have a look at how they perform before applying to the whole dataset.

5.1 Modelling on a micro subset

5.1.1 Subset dataset

set.seed(12)
in_micro <- caret::createDataPartition(dd[, target][[1]],
                                         p = 0.01,
                                         list = FALSE)
dd_micro <- dd[in_micro, ]

5.1.2 Create train / test

in_train <- caret::createDataPartition(dd_micro[, target][[1]],
                                       p = 0.80,
                                       list = FALSE)
train_micro <- dd_micro[in_train, ]
test_micro <- dd_micro[-in_train, ]

5.2 Random forest.

set.seed(12)

# find best mtry
b <- randomForest::tuneRF(train_micro[, not_target],
                          train_micro[,target][[1]],
                          ntreeTry = 100)
## mtry = 3  OOB error = 27.3% 
## Searching left ...
## mtry = 2     OOB error = 28.25% 
## -0.03461841 0.05 
## Searching right ...
## mtry = 6     OOB error = 27.86% 
## -0.02045633 0.05

best_mtry <- b[which(b[,2] == min(b[,2])), 1]

# create model
rf_micro <- randomForest::randomForest(x = train_micro[, not_target],
                                       y = train_micro[,target][[1]],
                                       mtry = best_mtry,
                                       ntree = 100,
                                       importance = TRUE,
                                       keep.forest = TRUE)

# accuracy
rf_micro_pred <- predict(rf_micro,
                         newdata = test_micro,
                         type = "class")

rf_cm_micro <-  caret::confusionMatrix(rf_micro_pred, test_micro[, target][[1]])
paste("Random forest model accuracy, partial dataset:", 
      scales::percent(rf_cm_micro$overall["Accuracy"]))
## [1] "Random forest model accuracy, partial dataset: 72.7%"

5.3 KNN

set.seed(12)

# find best k
best_k <- fastknn::fastknnCV(as.matrix(train_micro[, numeric_vars]),
                             train_micro[, target][[1]],
                             k = 3:15,
                             method = "vote",
                             folds = 5,
                             eval.metric = "overall_error")
# predict using the best k
knn_micro_pred <- fastknn::fastknn(as.matrix(train_micro[, numeric_vars]),
                 train_micro[, target][[1]],
                 as.matrix(test_micro[, numeric_vars]),
                 k = best_k$best_k)

# accuracy
knn_micro_acc <- 1 - fastknn::classLoss(actual = test_micro[, target][[1]],
                                        predicted = knn_micro_pred$class)
paste("KNN accuracy, partial dataset:",
      scales::percent(knn_micro_acc))
## [1] "KNN accuracy, partial dataset: 73%"
